    <section name="Welcome to Force Field X">
      <subsection name="Introduction">
        <table>
          <tr>
            <td width="600">
              <p>Force Field X is an open source polyglot software for molecular biophysics
                that targets open research questions in the areas of:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Understanding the effect of missense variants on protein structure, thermodynamics and molecular
                  phenotype.
                </li>
                <li>Prediction of the structure, thermodynamic stability and solubility of organic polymer crystals.
                </li>
                <li>Designing biomolecules in both soluble and crystalline environments.</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The graphical user interface (GUI) screenshot to the right shows "Compound 23",
                which was the 23rd molecule predicted as part of the CCDC crystal structure prediction series.
              </p>
              <p>
                <b>Performance</b>
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>For large systems such as the protein DHRF in water, FFX can offload simulations to a GPU using
                  OpenMM. Using the polarizable AMOEBA force field with PME electrostatics, DHRF in water executes at
                  ~20-40 nsec per day depending on GPU.
                </li>
                <li>For organic crystals with small unit cells and/or space group symmetry (e.g., Compound 23), FFX
                  utilizes a highly specialized CPU code path that achieves ~300 to 400 nsec per day of aggregate
                  sampling on a recent Intel processor.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </td>
            <td width="600">
              <p>
                <a href="manual.html">
                  <img src="images/ffx-gui.png" alt="Force Field X" width="600" align="right"/>
                </a>
              </p>
            </td>
          </tr>
